observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the management agreed to:
a) revisit the IRR of RA 9184, specifically its provisions on the procurement process during emergency circumstances to prevent recurrence of the document inconsistencies and to ensure that all procurement transactions of the Municipality are in accordance with the existing procurement rules and regulations;
b) provide a written and sufficient justification together with the documentation if available, to prevent the transaction from being disallowed.

We recommended and the management agreed that:
a) the MDRRM Officer;
i. specify the period of implementation during the planning stage for proper monitoring of the use of DRRMF; and
ii. optimally utilize the DRRM fund as per the approved budget.
b) The MDRRM Officer and Municipal Accountant;
i. discontinue transferring unexpended capital outlay to the Special Trust Fund, instead create and maintain a separate ledger for continuing appropriations under the general fund.
c) the Municipal Treasurer;
iii. set aside available cash to cater the approved LDRRMIP, so as not to hamper the PPAs scheduled for implement for the year.

We recommended and the Municipal Accountant agreed to present the originally appropriated amount for the Disaster Risk Reduction and Management (DRRM) Fund in the Notes to Financial Statements, instead of the adjusted budget, if target collections are not met pursuant to Republic Act No. 10121 and prepare necessary accounting entry to correct the overstatement of Cash – LCCA representing funds that should be transferred to Trust Liability-DRRM account.

We also reiterated the following recommendations:
b) for the Municipal Accountant to coordinate with Municipal Budget to establish the ending balance of the current year’s DRRM appropriations at the end of the year to determine the amount to be transferred from General Fund to Trust Fund;
c) for the Municipal Accountant to transfer the unexpended/unobligated QRF and MF-MOOE to the Special Trust Fund under the Trust Liability-DRRM account; and
d) for the Municipal Treasurer to fast track the process of transferring the unexpended/unobligated QRF and MF-MOOE to the Special Trust Fund.

We recommend that the Municipal Accountant with the involvement of the Local Chief Executive as the head of the agency:
a. Ensure that only Bonafide obligations of the agency are included and accurately recorded in the books of accounts;
b. Coordinate with the creditor bank regarding loan records to properly reflect the correct balances of the Loans Payable- Domestic Account of the Municipality;
c. Henceforth administer the proper recording to the transaction in the system and instruct the assigned personnel to prepare the necessary adjusting entries, if applicable; and

We recommend that:
a. the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer enhance forecasting of estimated revenue to ensure that collection thereof could be realize;
b. the Local Finance Committee employ trend analysis of actual income collected and consider the results during budget planning to ensure realistic and feasible budget;
c. the Municipal Treasurer analyze collection shortfalls/deficiencies to identify and implement revenue-enhancing strategies to further improve collection efficiency; and
d. the Local Chief Executive adopt a more conservative budget to minimize the accumulation of cash deficit and ensure proper funding of different projects, programs and activities embodied in the annual budget.

Therefore, we reiterated our previous recommendation and the management agreed that the following and the Municipal Accountant:
a. reconcile the discrepancies between the ending balances of CY 2021 unexpended QRF and Mitigation Fund-MOOE, as reported in the Detailed & Summarize Reports of Receipt & Utilization and the Notes to Financial Statement (NTFS), and effect necessary adjusting entry thereafter;
b. in coordination with Municipal Budget to establish the ending balance of the current year’s DRRM appropriations at the end of the year to determine the amount to be transferred from General Fund to Trust Fund;
c. transfer the unexpended/unobligated QRF and MF-MOOE to the Special Trust Fund under the Trust Liability-DRRM account; and
d. the Municipal Treasurer to fast track the process of transferring the unexpended/unobligated QRF and MF-MOOE to the Special Trust Fund.

We recommended and the management agreed on the following:
a. directs the Municipal Accountant and the LDRRMO to verify the veracity of all data with discrepancies, as indicated in Tables 3-4, and after proper reconciliation procedures, effect necessary adjustments therefor;
b. instructs the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the discrepancies between the ending balances of CY 2021 unexpended QRF and Mitigation Fund-MOOE, as reported in the Detailed & Summarize Reports of Receipt & Utilization and the Notes to Financial Statement (NTFS), and effect necessary adjusting entry thereafter;
c. requires the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the LDRRMO to henceforth, establish and conduct regular reconciliation of all LDRRMF components, such as the current year appropriation, STF and continuing Appropriation; and
d. instructs Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the MDRRMO to prepare and submit Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF on or before the 15th day after the end of each Month through the LDRRMC and Local Development Council (LDC) to the COA auditor of the LGU.

Therefore, we recommended and the management agreed to do the following:
• Make necessary effort to provide depreciation if information of the PPEs not provided with depreciation by other Offices/Departments and provide the depreciation if complete data has been gathered;
• Check the accuracy of information entered in the accounting system and make sure all data of the PPEs are provided and ensure correct calculation of depreciation on these PPE;
• Recompute the depreciation once entered into the system to verify and establish the correct results;
• Transfer completed and long outstanding PPEs of Trust Fund to the General Fund and subject the same to depreciation;
• Contact the service provider of the accounting system so that correct and complete details of the PPE in system will be provided and ensure calculation of depreciation on these properties;
• Make adjustments on the presentation of properties which were reflected with over provision of depreciation.
• Make adjustments in the books on identified PPE subject for reclassification and provide depreciation on these PPEs subject for depreciation as considered in accounting parlance
• Check the accuracy of information in the accounting system utilized to ensure calculation of depreciation on all properties of the Municipality
• Review, verify and make the necessary adjustments on properties under 20% development fund with accumulated depreciation more than its acquisition cost.
• Require the Accounting Office to prepare and maintain Property Equipment Ledger Cards, as required in the Property and Supply Management System Handbook.
For the Municipal General Services Officer to:
• Develop procedures to mitigate and reduce reconciling balances of PPE in order to report an accurate and complete balance of the account;
• Assign Two (2) or more permanent employees in the General Services Office to prepare, maintain and update Property/Equipment Cards every month, and to prepare and to submit the Physical Inventory Report on or before every January 31 of succeeding years as required in the Property and Supply Management System Handbook.
For the Municipal Mayor to:
• Augment manpower needs of the MGSO, if budget permits
• Send MGSO personnel to proper training / seminar on Government Management and Disposal of properties
• Provide proper storage facility to safe keep the office supplies, equipment, spare parts, and waste materials or unserviceable properties of the Municipality of Tantangan.

Therefore, we recommended and the management agreed to do the following:
• Locate and trace down the documents to support the adjusting entries on the long outstanding reconciling items
• Request copies from the bank of the debit memos and credit memos issued for proper recording in the books;
• Record adjustments for valid reconciling items per books as reflected in the BRS prepared;
• Locate the stale checks if it is still available with the Municipal Treasurer and make the necessary procedures for replacing the check. If the check is not available, confirm the payable account with the payee and make the proper procedures for replacing the check. If no response was received, make the necessary adjustments with the books.
